The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Saturday, April 10, 2004 				Metro Recommends
				 																THE CD				 																																	(Eric Clapton) This four-CD set featuring milestone numbers from live concerts in the Seventies, reiterates Claptons unstinting passion for American blues music. Check out for the biting blasts from his Stratocaster when he jams with Carlos Santana in Eyesight to the Blind THE BOOK				 																																	(Sarnath Banerjee) A tale of Delhi through the eyes of a Calcuttan living there, complete with post-modern Ibn Battutas and know-all pavement booksellers. Hilarious, witty and occasionally serious, Banerjees first graphic novel (Indias first too) is a must-read THE EXHIBITION				 																																	(Sasha, 27, Mirza Ghalib Street, on till April 20) Sasha has put together yet another colourful ensemble of saris, casualwear, accessories and home linens made by crafts people and womens cooperatives. The exhibition will be inaugurated by social activist Nafisa Ali (picture above) and painter Wasim Kapoor on Saturday at 11 am THE SEMINAR				 																																	(Seagull Arts amp; Media Resource Centre, April 10, 2 pm to 5 pm) Urvashi Butalia, Moinak Biswas, Ranabir Samaddar and Kavita Panjabi will speak at a seminar on the experience of borders and partitions. A presentation by Arindam Sen on the problems faced by inhabitants on Indias eastern borders will follow 

